{"cursor":"6735","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" {{Infobox scientist |name = Sherwin B. Nuland, M.D. |image = |image_size =\n |caption = |birth_date = December 1930 |birth_place = Bronx, New York\n |death_date = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = American |ethnicity =\n |fields = Surgeon; Author; Educator |workplaces = Yale University School of\n Medicine |alma_mater = New York University & Yale University School of Medicine\n |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students\n = |known_for = Professor of Surgery; Medical Ethicist; Historian of Medicine;\n Modern Philosopher |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences =\n |influenced = |awards = |religion = |signature = |footnotes = }}\n\n'Dr. Sherwin Nuland' (born December 1930) is an American surgeon and author who\nteaches bioethics, history of medicine, and medicine at the Yale University\nSchool of Medicine and, upon occasion, bioethics and history of medicine at Yale\nCollege. His 1994 book How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter was a New\nYork Times Best Seller and won the National Book Award for Nonfiction. [http://www.nationalbook.org/nba1994.html \"National Book Awards â\n1994\"]. National Book Foundation. Retrieved 2012-03-24.\n\nNuland has written non-academic articles for [[The New Yorker]], The New York\nTimes, [[The New Republic]], [[Time (magazine)|Time]], and the [[New York Review\nof Books]]. Perhaps his greatest work, however, is his first-generation American\nautobiography of his own painful coming of age as a son of immigrants, \".\" He is\na fellow of the Hastings Center, an independent bioethics research institution.\n[http://www.thehastingscenter.org/About/Default.aspx?id=902 The Hastings\nCenter] Hastings Center Fellows. Retrieved 2010-11-06.\n","linknr":184,"url":"Sherwin_Nuland","recorded":1376425016,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Sherwin_B._Nuland&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Sherwin_B._Nuland&action=edit","/